0.body: We are going to use Open Watcom V2.0 as our compiler, Visual Studio Code as our code editor, and DosBox as our DOS emulator.
0.title: Installation

1.body: Let's start by installing the easier one first. It's as simple as downloading it from Visual Studio Code's Website and installing it. You can also install it via winget by running this command: winget install -e --id Microsoft.VisualStudioCode We also need to install a few Extensions to make life easier for us. First, let's open the Extensions menu. There are few ways to do that: Look for this icon On the left side and click it! Open Command Palette (with Ctrl+Shift+P or F1) and type View: Show Extensions Use the default keyboard shortcut : Ctrl+Shift+X From there search and install these extensions: C/C++ Makefile Tools

13.body: BIOS by default has few video mode that we can use: AL [1] Type Format Cell Colors Adapter [2] Address 0x00 text 40x25 8x8 [3] 16/8 (shades) CGA 0xB8000 0x01 text 40x25 8x8 [3] 16/8 CGA 0xB8000 0x02 text 80x25 8x8 [3] 16/8 (shades) CGA 0xB8000 0x03 text 80x25 8x8 [3] 16/8 CGA 0xB8000 0x04 graphics 320x200 8x8 4 CGA 0xB8000 0x05 graphics 320x200 8x8 4 (shades) CGA 0xB8000 0x06 graphics 640x200 8x8 2 CGA 0xB8000 0x07 text 80x25 9x14 [4] 2 MDA, EGA 0xB0000 0x08 graphics 160x200 8x8 16 PCjr IDK 0x09 graphics 320x200 8x8 16 PCjr IDK 0x0A graphics 650x200 8x8 4 PCjr IDK 0x0D [5] graphics 320x200 8x8 16 EGA 0xA0000 0x0E graphics 640x200 8x8 16 EGA 0xA0000 0x0F graphics 640x350 8x14 2 EGA 0xA0000 0x10 graphics 640x350 8x14 4 64K EGA 0xA0000 0x10 graphics 640x350 8x14 16 128K EGA, VGA 0xA0000 0x11 graphics 640x480 8x16 2 MCGA, VGA 0xA0000 0x12 graphics 640x480 8x16 16 VGA 0xA0000 0x13 graphics 320x200 8x16 256 VGA 0xA0000 adding 0x80 to these values will stop BIOS from clearing the screen. EGA is fully compatible with CGA, and VGA is fully compatible with CGA and EGA. CGA=8x8, EGA=8x14, and VGA=9x16. MDA and EGA=9x14, VGA=9x16, LCD=8x8. 0B, and 0C are reserved for EGA BIOS.

2.body: Open Watcom V2.0 is only available for Windows and Linux (dos, win16, and os2 are also supported). I'm only going to cover Windows and Linux, macOS users may have to use Wine but I can't test it because I don't have any machine running macOS. First we have to download Watcom so go to GitHub from there go to Releases then select the latest build ( 2023-07-02-Build at the time of writing)
2.title: Open Watcom V2.0

3.body: Download open-watcom-2_0-c-win-x64.exe and run it. Read the EULA and press I Agree. Select a folder to install Watcom (I use C:\Dev\Programs\WATCOM but you can use any folder) Select Full installation and hit next Press next If you have installed it before, you will be prompted about what to do about some DLLs Select Install the new file and keep existing file and select Use the current choice for all subsequent DLLs Select Modify local machine environment variables and hit OK Select Don't Modify associations and press OK There is one more step that I'm going to explain later. (follow DOSBox installation)
3.title: Windows

4.body:
Download open-watcom-2_0-c-linux-x64. Extract it and copy it to /usr/bin/watcom And add these lines to the top of ~/.profile and ~/.bashrc export WATCOM=/usr/bin/watcom
export PATH=$WATCOM/binl64:$WATCOM/binl:$PATH Restart the terminal and run wpp in terminal and if you see Open Watcom C++ x86 16-bit Optimizing Compiler ... then you have installed it successfully!
4.title: Linux

6.body: Run this command in cmd winget install dosbox After installing it, open windows search and search for Edit the system environment variables and open it. On the button of the opened window, there will be a button called Environment Variables... press it! You'll see two lists we're going to change, the top one called User Variables for $(YOUR_USER_NAME) Find the variable called path and double click it. Press the new button and type the installation location of DOSBox. (default is C:\Program Files (x86)\DOSBox-0.74-3) Now open a new cmd and run dosbox and if it starts DOSBox then you have installed it successfully! Press the new button again and type the installation location of Watcom and add \binnt64. (so it'll be C:\Dev\Programs\WATCOM\binnt64 for me) Go back to the page that you found path in. And make these variables: (instead of ###WATCOM### write your Watcom install location without a \ at the end) WATCOM = ###WATCOM### EDPATH = %WATCOM%\eddat INCLUDE = %WATCOM%\H;%WATCOM%\H\NT;%WATCOM%\H\NT\DIRECTX;%WATCOM%\H\NT\DDK; WHTMLHELP = %WATCOM%\BINNT\HELP WIPFC = %WATCOM%\WIPFC Then press okay until you close all the windows (don't close with X) Now open cmd and run wpp and if you see Open Watcom C++ x86 16-bit Optimizing Compiler ... then you have installed Watcom successfully!
6.title: Windows

7.body: Run this command and that's it! sudo apt-get install dosbox Installation has only been tested on Windows. Linux test is pending...
7.title: Linux

8.title: Hello World

9.body: main.obj : main.cpp wpp -0 -bt=dos -ms -s -wx -zq -fo="$@" "$<" wpp is the Open Watcom C++ x86 16-bit Optimizing Compiler -0 : Only use 8086 instruction set -bt=dos : Operating system is dos -ms : Small memory model -s : Remove stack overflow checks -wx : Set warning level to maximum setting -zq : Operate quietly (display only error messages) -fo="$@" : Output file is $@ ($@=main.obj in this case) "$<" : Input file is $< ($<=main.cpp in this case) test.exe : main.obj wlink system dos option dosseg option quiet file { $< } name $@ wlink is the Open Watcom Linker system dos : Target system is DOS option dosseg : The DOSSEG option tells the Open Watcom Linker to order segments in a special way. option quiet : Don't print anything other than errors file { $< } : Input files ($<=main.obj in this case) name $@ : Output file name $@ ($@=test.exe in this case) clean : .SYMBOLIC -del test.exe main.obj main.err Deletes files test.exe main.obj main.err run : test.exe dosbox test.exe Runs test.exe with DOSBox you can find source code for this chapter at GitHub
